# Nocturne Windows Widget — Privacy Policy

_Last updated: 21 June 2026_

This policy describes how the **Nocturne Windows 11 Widget** ("the widget") handles
your data. The widget is free, open-source software published by the Nightscout
Foundation. Its source code is available at
[github.com/nightscout/nocturne](https://github.com/nightscout/nocturne).

<Callout type="info" title="The short version">
  The widget talks only to the Nocturne server you choose. Your diabetes data and
  your sign-in tokens stay on your PC and that server. The Nightscout Foundation
  does not receive, collect, store, or have any access to your data, and there is
  no analytics or tracking of any kind.
</Callout>

## What the widget accesses

When you connect the widget to your Nocturne server, it requests **read-only**
access to the data it displays:

- Glucose readings and trend (`glucose.read`)
- Treatments, including insulin-on-board and carbs-on-board (`treatments.read`)
- Device and pump status (`devices.read`)
- Therapy settings used for display (`therapy.read`)

The widget never requests write access and cannot modify, add, or delete any data
on your server.

## Where your data goes

The widget communicates **directly** between your PC and the Nocturne server you
enter during setup. There are no intermediary servers. Your diabetes data is
fetched over the network solely to render the widget and is held only transiently
in memory for display — it is not written to disk and is not transmitted anywhere
else.

The Nightscout Foundation operates no servers in this flow and receives no data.
If you connect to a self-hosted Nocturne instance, your data never leaves
infrastructure you control.

## Authentication and credentials

The widget signs in using the OAuth 2.0 Device Authorization flow
([RFC 8628](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8628)). You approve a short
code on your Nocturne site; no password or long-lived token is ever entered into
or stored by the widget.

The resulting access and refresh tokens are stored locally and encrypted using the
**Windows Credential Manager**, scoped to your Windows user account. These tokens
are sent only to your Nocturne server, only to retrieve the data above and to
refresh the session.

## Removing access

You can disconnect at any time:

- Choose **Sign out** in the widget's customize panel, which revokes the tokens and
  deletes them from Windows Credential Manager; or
- Revoke the "Nocturne Windows Widget" authorization from your Nocturne account's
  connected-apps settings at any time.

Uninstalling the widget removes the application; signing out first ensures the
stored tokens are also revoked on the server.

## Telemetry, analytics, and advertising

The widget contains **no** analytics, telemetry, crash reporting, advertising, or
third-party tracking SDKs. It makes no network connections other than to the
Nocturne server you configure.

## Children's privacy

The widget collects no data and is a display surface for a Nocturne server you
already use. Any data handling is governed by that server's own policies.

## Changes to this policy

Material changes to this policy will be reflected here with an updated date. The
current version always lives at this URL.

## Contact

Questions about this policy can be raised via the project's issue tracker at
[github.com/nightscout/nocturne/issues](https://github.com/nightscout/nocturne/issues).
